ernatively, could invoking classes through Groovy's MetaClass reach methods that are usually off-limits? There’s a lot to unpack here!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring method accessibility**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether I could call a method from a Java class within the same package as the library. However, tests shouldn’t be within the library’s packages. What if I tried creating a subclass of RestAssuredProxySelector and accessed the metaClass? But there’s no class$ available. While Java source might have restrictions on package-private, Groovy tests could have more flexibility. I’m also considering if the dynamic-access coverage might be excluding certain MethodHandle calls. There’s so much to unpack!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing dynamic access reports**\\n\\nIt looks like the test passed, but I’m wondering about the dynamic access tool. It probably reports from agent logs that exclude dynamic access if the caller frame is \\\"io.restassured.internal.proxy.RestAssuredProxySelector.class$\\\". If the test helper invokes it, it should be covered, right? Although, maybe the agent wasn't running during that specific test, which could explain everything being native only. But the XML shows something different. There’s definitely a puzzle here to piece together!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing test execution issues**\\n\\nIt seems like there’s a possibility that newly covered call sites aren't appearing because they ran only the previous tests before the recent changes. I need to think about adding a second test method dedicated to a specific class with a different target in the same active class. There might be issues with the HTTP path throwing errors before reaching the helper under the agent. I wonder if the JUnit didn't run the helper due to potentially stale XML.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test coverage improvements**\\n\\nI’m thinking about adding a direct `@Test` tha